      <h1>Understanding the Standard Deduction: How It Lowers Your Tax</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 17, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>5 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">The standard deduction is one of the easiest ways to lower your taxable income. Here is what the standard deduction is, how it is determined, and how it compares to itemized deductions.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Tax relief:</strong> The standard deduction reduces the portion of your income that is subject to federal income tax. You subtract this flat amount from your gross income automatically, no receipts required.</div>

      <h2>What is the standard deduction?</h2>
      <p>The standard deduction is a fixed dollar amount that the IRS allows you to subtract from your Adjusted Gross Income (AGI) to determine your taxable income. By lowering your taxable income, the standard deduction reduces your overall tax liability. The specific deduction amount is adjusted annually for inflation and varies based on your filing status, age, and whether you are blind.</p>

      <h2>Standard deduction limits compared</h2>
      <p>Your deduction is determined by how you file your taxes. The primary categories are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Single Filers:</strong> Individuals filing alone.</li>
        <li><strong>Married Filing Jointly:</strong> Couples filing a single return together.</li>
        <li><strong>Head of Household:</strong> Single individuals who pay more than half the cost of keeping up a home for a qualifying dependent.</li>
        <li><strong>Married Filing Separately:</strong> Married couples filing individual tax returns.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Standard deduction vs. Itemized deductions</h2>
      <p>When filing your taxes, you must choose between taking the standard deduction or itemizing your deductions. You cannot do both.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Standard Deduction:</strong> A no-questions-asked, flat deduction. It is simple, fast, and does not require tracking expenses. The vast majority of US taxpayers (over 85%) choose this option.</li>
        <li><strong>Itemized Deductions:</strong> The sum of individual deductible expenses you incurred during the year. These include mortgage interest, state and local taxes (SALT) up to $10,000, medical expenses exceeding 7.5% of your AGI, and charitable donations.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>The Golden Rule:</strong> Calculate both, and choose whichever option provides the larger deduction. If the sum of your itemized expenses exceeds the standard deduction amount for your filing status, you should itemize to lower your tax bill.</p>

      <h2>Additional deduction for seniors and the blind</h2>
      <p>Taxpayers who are 65 or older, or who are legally blind, are entitled to an additional standard deduction amount. If you are both 65+ and blind, the deduction increases even further, providing additional tax relief.</p>
